*Objective:*
This project aims to verify the Auditory Precision Hypothesis-L2,
which posits that precise domain-general auditory processing underlies successful
second language (L2) speech learning (CITE).
We will address gaps in previous research by employing a longitudinal paradigm
and testing a novel learner profile, namely beginner learners of French
in a classroom setting.
Results of this project will advance our understanding of the nature of second language
acquisition (SLA) and help evolve classroom-based language pedagogy practices.

*Context:*
Adults learning a second language rarely attain native-like oral proficiency.
Research in SLA has proposed various factors which have the potential to influence
the learning trajectory and final outcome.
Domain-general auditory skills, broadly defined to include acuity (one's sensitivity
to minute differences in individual acoustic dimensions such as pitch and duration)
and audio-motor integration (the capacity to capture the acoustic characteristics of
sounds and convert them into motor action), were first shown to affect first language
acquisition (CITE).
However, a number of recent studies have suggested that different components of
domain-general auditory skills are also uniquely associated with different aspects of
L2 speech learning (CITE).
Yet, the exact relevance of these skills also appears to depend on several additional
factors such as the learning environment (naturalistic vs. classroom-based) and
overall L2 proficiency.
To our knowledge, no other study has examined whether the same predictive effects
of domain-general auditory skills can be observed among beginner learners in a
traditional classroom setting, with limited exposure to the target language.
Further, the generalizability of existing research findings is questionable, because
only learners of English have been recruited and studied.
These limitations motivate our focus on beginner learners of French.

*Methodology:*
We will recruit 45 participants from "advanced beginner" French classes offered by
universities across Montreal.
Participants' speech data will be collected at two time points, once at the beginning
of the semester and once more at the end.
To tap into multiple aspects of participants' oral proficiency, we will use several
production tasks ranging from highly controlled (reading individual words in a carrier sentence)
to semi-spontaneous (storyboard narration).
In addition, we will measure participants' domain-general auditory skills using tests
developed by (CITE), which they have made free and publicly accessible on the site
_Tools for Second Language Speech Research and Teaching_ (CITE).
We will also include a number of other instruments to control for potential confounding
variables such as working memory, overall French proficiency, and other language-related
experience.
We will analyze participants' speech data, focusing on gains in oral proficiency across
the two time points, by employing both subjective rater judgments and objective
acoustic measurements.
Finally, we will conduct statistical analyses using mixed effect models to explore the
predictive power of domain-general auditory skills on our learners' oral proficiency
gains.

*Feasibility and supervision:*
As I have previously conducted a similar research project in my undergraduate studies,
certain components such as the oral production tasks and working memory test have
already been developed and tested.
Moreover, all but one planned component are computer-based and online, facilitating the
training of research assistants and allowing for flexible and simultaneous data collection
in different locations.
Montreal's status as a francophone city with a blooming immigrant population makes
it an ideal place to recruit L2 learners of French.
Finally, my supervisor Heather Goad, and Professor Daphnée Simard whom I collaborate
with at UQÀM, are both experts in second language acquisition.
My research aligns with the objectives of the Centre for Research on Brain,
Language and Music (CRBLM), of which both professors are members.

